s of Low-Income Mothers and Youth? Evidence from the Moving to Opportunity Experiment -- tChapter 12. Teens, Mental Health, and Moving to Opportunity -- tChapter 13. Changing the Geography of Opportunity by Helping Poor Households Move Out of Concentrated Poverty: Neighborhood Effects and Policy Design -- tPart IV. Segregation: The Power of Place -- tChapter 14. Are Mixed Neighborhoods Always Unstable? Two-Sided and One-Sided Tipping -- tChapter 15. Preferences for Hispanic Neighborhoods -- tChapter 16. Increasing Diversity and the Future of U.S. Housing Segregation -- tChapter 17. Understanding Racial Segregation: What Is Known About the Effect of Housing Discrimination? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDoes the place where you lived as a child affect your health as an adult? To what degree does your neighbor's success influence your own potential? The importance of place is increasingly recognized in urban research as an important variable in understanding individual and household outcomes. Place matters in education, physical health, crime, violence, housing, family income, mental health, and discrimination—issues that determine the quality of life, especially among low-income residents of urban areas.Neighborhood and Life Chances: How Place Matters in Modern America brings together researchers from a range of disciplines to present the findings of studies in the fields of education, health, and housing. The results are intriguing and surprising, particularly the debate over Moving to Opportunity, an experiment conducted by the Department of Housing and Urban Development, designed to test directly the effects of relocating individuals away from areas of concentrated poverty. Its results, while strong in some respects, showed very different outcomes for boys and girls, with girls more likely than boys to experience positive outcomes. Reviews of the literature in education and health, supplemented by new research, demonstrate that the problems associated with residing in a negative environment are indisputable, but also suggest the directions in which solutions may lie.The essays collected in this volume give readers a clear sense of the magnitude of contemporary challenges in metropolitan America and of the role that place plays in reinforcing them. Although the contributors suggest many practical immediate interventions, they also recognize the vital importance of continued long-term efforts to rectify place-based limitations on lifetime opportunities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aAmerican History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aPublic Policy.  aSociology.  aUrban Studies.1 aBirch, Eugenie L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBranas, Charles C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCard, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClampet-Lundquist, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCove, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurrie, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeFina, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuarte, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl Komi, Mohamed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerreira, Fernando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalster, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGennetian, Lisa A., econtributor.4ctb4h